  {"t":"lead","html":"Berlin gets sold as Cold War history and techno myths, and both are real. But the thing that actually defines the city right now is a street most visitors never hear about: <strong>Sonnenallee</strong>, in Neukölln, which Berliners have nicknamed <strong>the Arab Street</strong>. This guide covers both halves of Berlin — the sights everyone comes for, and the food street almost nobody sends you to."},
  {"t":"p","html":"Here's the part that makes us different: every business we feature in this city sits on or within two blocks of Sonnenallee. Its Arab character goes back to 1975, when Lebanese refugees fleeing the civil war began settling North Neukölln; Syrian, Palestinian and Yemeni communities followed in the decades after. Neukölln today counts roughly 33,000 Arab residents — about a quarter of Berlin's entire Arab population — and it's one of the largest concentrations of Levantine food outside the Middle East itself, all walkable in an afternoon. We go deep on it in our <a class='inline' href='/berlin/where-to-eat-in-berlin/'>Sonnenallee food crawl</a>; here are seven places to start."},
