  {"t":"lead","html":"Berlin's food reputation runs on currywurst and döner, and both earn it. But the best Middle Eastern food outside the Middle East itself is a short train ride from the Brandenburg Gate, on one street in Neukölln most visitors never hear about. This is a food crawl down Sonnenallee — Syrian shawarma, Palestinian falafel, Yemeni cooking, Damascene sweets, halal butchers and Levantine grocers, roughly in walking order."},
  {"t":"h2","text":"Sonnenallee: how a Beirut street ended up in Neukölln"},
  {"t":"p","html":"Berliners have called this street <strong>the Arab Street</strong> for years — a nickname common enough that Middle East Eye, The National and the South China Morning Post have all covered it. It started in 1975, when Lebanese refugees fleeing the civil war settled North Neukölln; Syrian, Palestinian and Yemeni communities followed in the decades after. Neukölln today has roughly 33,000 Arab residents — about a quarter of Berlin's entire Arab population — and Middle Eastern-origin residents make up close to 18% (around 55,000 people) of the borough."},
  {"t":"p","html":"We know this street because we mapped it ourselves: our own count of roughly 30 businesses on and just off Sonnenallee is one of the densest, most self-contained Arab strips we've seen anywhere — a halal butcher next to a goldsmith next to a falafel counter next to a bridal shop. This guide covers the 15 food, sweets and grocery spots from that list, in the order you'd actually walk them."},
