  {"t":"h2","text":"Where döner and currywurst fit in"},
  {"t":"p","html":"Sonnenallee is the deep cut, but it's part of Berlin's wider street-food identity, not apart from it. <strong>Currywurst</strong> was invented right here, by Herta Heuwer in 1949, and it's still the sentimental mascot of Berlin street food: sliced sausage, curried ketchup, done in two minutes."},
  {"t":"p","html":"<strong>Döner</strong> is the bigger story. Berlin-style döner-in-bread — meat, tomato, cucumber, cabbage and sauce folded into flatbread — is widely credited to Kadir Nurman in Kreuzberg in 1972, though the claim is genuinely disputed, with competing stories and a possible earlier Istanbul origin. Whoever invented it, döner is now Berlin's biggest-selling street food, ahead of currywurst — and Sonnenallee's shawarma shops are a close cousin of the same tradition. Order both and you'll taste the family resemblance."},
  {"t":"tip","head":"Pair it with the Türkenmarkt","html":"Neukölln's other great food institution is the <strong>Maybachufer canal-side market</strong> (the 'Türkenmarkt') — Turkish and Middle Eastern produce, cheese, bread and fabric, historically Tuesday and Friday afternoons. Confirm the day before you build a trip around it; if it lines up, it pairs naturally with a Sonnenallee afternoon."},
  {"t":"h2","text":"How to actually do the crawl"},
  {"t":"p","html":"Sonnenallee has its own S-Bahn station, or take the U7 to Karl-Marx-Straße or Rathaus Neukölln and walk in. Go in the afternoon rather than right after lunch: start with a shawarma or falafel main, walk it off past the goldsmiths, barbershops and the bridal boutique that round out the rest of the strip, then land on kunafa or warbat when you're ready. Two to three hours does it easily, and you'll still have only scratched the fifteen places above — that's rather the point. Go back."},
